8 Macro System
**************

Macros transform code at expansion time.  They receive unevaluated
arguments and produce new code to be evaluated.

     (defmacro when (condition . body)
       `(if ,condition (progn ,@body)))

     (when (> x 0)
       (print "positive")
       (print x))
     ;; Expands to: (if (> x 0) (progn (print "positive") (print x)))

   Key points:
   • Macro arguments are *not* evaluated before the macro runs
   • The macro body produces a new expression (the *expansion*)
   • The expansion is then evaluated in the calling environment
   • Use quasiquote (‘`’) with unquote (‘,’) and splice (‘,@’) to build
     expansions


File: tlisp.info,  Node: Tail Call Optimization,  Next: Standalone Runtime,  Prev: Macro System,  Up: Top

9 Tail Call Optimization
************************

T-Lisp optimizes recursive calls in tail position to use constant stack
space.  A call is in tail position when it is the last thing a function
does.

     ;; Tail-recursive factorial
     (defun factorial (n acc)
       (if (<= n 1)
           acc
           (factorial (- n 1) (* n acc))))

     (defun fact (n)
       (factorial n 1))

     (fact 100)  ; Works without stack overflow

   The recursive call to ‘factorial’ is in tail position because it is
the result of the ‘if’ expression in the else branch.


