10 Standalone Runtime
*********************

T-Lisp can run outside the editor through the standalone ‘tlisp’ CLI.
The standalone runtime uses the same parser, evaluator, macro system,
and module registry as the editor, but registers a runtime profile for
command-line work: stdout/stdin, filesystem primitives, system
primitives, documentation helpers, and standalone module loading.

10.1 CLI Usage
==============

     bun run tlisp                  Start the REPL
     bun run tlisp -- -e '(+ 1 2)'  Evaluate one expression
     bin/tlisp script.tlisp         Run a script
     bun run build:tlisp            Compile dist/tlisp with Bun
     ./dist/tlisp -e '(+ 1 2)'

   Script files may begin with a Unix shebang such as:

     #!/usr/bin/env tlisp

   The CLI strips the shebang before evaluating the file.

10.2 REPL Behavior
==================

The REPL keeps definitions across inputs, supports multiline forms by
tracking balanced parentheses, and defines Clojure-like result bindings:

‘*1’
     Most recent result.
‘*2’
     Second most recent result.
‘*3’
     Third most recent result.
‘*e’
     Most recent error message, or nil.

   Special REPL commands are ‘help’, ‘env’, ‘clear’, ‘exit’, and ‘quit’.

10.3 Standalone Module Loading
==============================

The standalone loader resolves modules in this order:

  1. Embedded standard-library modules such as ‘std/strings’.
  2. Files relative to the current working directory.
  3. Directories listed in ‘TLISP_PATH’.

   Module names map predictably to ‘.tlisp’ paths; for example,
‘std/strings’ maps to ‘std/strings.tlisp’.  Path traversal in module
names is rejected.


