11 Module System
****************

The module system gives T-Lisp files explicit public APIs and scoped
imports.  It is used by the editor's built-in T-Lisp libraries and by
the standalone runtime.

11.1 Defining Modules
=====================

Use ‘defmodule’ to create a module.  Exported names form the module's
public API:

     (defmodule math/tools
       (export double square)

       (defun double (n) (* n 2))
       (defun square (n) (* n n)))

   Module bodies run in an isolated environment whose parent is the
builtins environment.  Exported names are available to callers through
‘require-module’.

11.2 Importing Modules
======================

Use ‘:as’ for qualified access:

     (require-module math/tools :as tools)
     (tools/double 10)

   Use ‘:import’ for selected unqualified names:

     (require-module math/tools :import (square))
     (square 5)

   The parser accepts both the colon syntax shown above and
parser-stripped forms such as ‘as’ and ‘import’; source code should
prefer the colon form.

11.3 Module Introspection
=========================

Inside the editor, module registry information is exposed through the
functions documented in *note Editor API --- Modules::.  In the
standalone runtime, ‘loaded-modules’, ‘doc’, and ‘apropos’ provide basic
discovery helpers.


