28 Editor API -- Minor Modes
****************************

Minor modes are buffer-local feature modes.  Active global minor modes
apply to existing buffers and future buffers unless a buffer has an
explicit local override.

 -- Function: define-minor-mode name description [lighter global]
     Register a minor mode.  This low-level helper records the mode
     name, description, lighter, and whether it supports global
     activation.  Built in T-Lisp mode files define the user-facing
     commands such as ‘line-numbers-mode’ and
     ‘global-line-numbers-mode’.

   Generated mode commands follow the Emacs-style argument rule used by
the built-ins: no argument toggles, ‘t’ or a positive number enables,
and ‘nil’, zero, or a negative number disables.

 -- Function: minor-mode-register name description [lighter]
     Register or update a minor mode.

 -- Function: minor-mode-set-keymap name keymap
     Associate an existing T-Lisp keymap value with a minor mode.

 -- Function: minor-mode-toggle name
     Toggle NAME for the current buffer.

 -- Function: minor-mode-set name state
     Enable or disable NAME for the current buffer.

 -- Function: minor-mode-active-p name
     Return true when NAME is active in the current buffer.

 -- Function: minor-mode-list-active
     Return active minor mode names for the current buffer.

 -- Function: minor-mode-list-all
     Return all registered minor mode names.

 -- Function: minor-mode-lighter name
     Return NAME's status-line lighter.

 -- Function: minor-mode-list-lighters
     Return lighters for active minor modes in the current buffer.

 -- Function: minor-mode-global-p name
     Return whether NAME supports globalized behavior.

 -- Function: global-minor-mode-set name state
     Enable or disable NAME globally.  Disabling removes global-sourced
     activations while preserving explicit buffer-local re-enables.

 -- Function: global-minor-mode-active-p name
     Return whether NAME is globally active.

 -- Function: global-minor-mode-list-active
     Return active global minor mode names.


